Hi,

I searched around to see if anyone&#39;s submitted this bug. I didn&#39;t
find a dupe, so I&#39;ll go ahead and post; apologies if it&#39;s already known.

In Assert#format(String, Object, Object), a NullPointerException is
thrown if either param &quot;expected&quot; or &quot;actual&quot; is null and the other is
*the string* &quot;null&quot;. Here are a couple test cases demonstrating this:

@Test(expected=NullPointerException.class)
public void confirmError() {
assertEquals(null, &quot;null&quot;);
}

@Test(expected=NullPointerException.class)
public void confirmErrorToo() {
assertEquals(&quot;null&quot;, null);
}

This is because Assert#format is trying to print extended information
when two objects are visually identical but semantically different;
namely, it wants to display the class names as well as the values,
doing a Object#getClass() without checking if the object is null.

Here&#39;s a possible fix:

static String format(String message, Object expected, Object actual) {
String formatted = &quot;&quot;;
if (message != null && !message.equals(&quot;&quot;)) {
formatted = message + &quot; &quot;;
}

String expectedString = String.valueOf(expected);
String actualString = String.valueOf(actual);

if (expected == null) {
return formatted + &quot;expected: &lt;null&gt; but was: &quot;
+ actual.getClass().getName() + &quot;&lt;&quot; + actualString + &quot;&gt;&quot;;
} else if (actual == null) {
return formatted + &quot;expected: &quot; + expected.getClass().getName()
+ &quot;&lt;&quot; + expectedString + &quot;&gt; but was: &lt;null&gt;&quot;;
} else if (expectedString.equals(actualString)) {
return formatted + &quot;expected: &quot; + expected.getClass().getName()
+ &quot;&lt;&quot; + expectedString + &quot;&gt; but was: &quot;
+ actual.getClass().getName() + &quot;&lt;&quot; + actualString + &quot;&gt;&quot;;
} else {
return formatted + &quot;expected:&lt;&quot; + expectedString + &quot;&gt; but was:&lt;&quot;
+ actualString + &quot;&gt;&quot;;
}
}

The assumption here is that actual and expected will never *both* be
null. Right?

